          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> TND: 3 Archetypes -->REAL<--<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=12670'>Matthew "Swamp Hyren" Morison</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=12670&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 19, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Well, I&#39;m going to skip the intro this time and dive right in, as I really have no idea as how to introdouce this, but, here I am telling you how to build a deck staying true to a theme. <br />
<br />
Oh, by the way, all the decks here assume you play 40 card decks. If you don&#39;t, then start. You are not permtted to read this if you have a deck with 41+ cards. I will come to your house and gouge out your eyes with a dull spoon. So go cut down. <br />
<br />
NOW! <br />
Yes, I&#39;m watching you.. <br />
Anyways, unto my topic.. <br />
<br />
AGRRO: Short for aggressive, or perhaps agrrivating. This deck will pummel you down and keep slamming you. You are under constant pressure and MUST play things to match theirs, or you will surely fall to seemingly endless discard and attacks, which brings me on how to build an aggro deck. <br />
<br />
RECIPE FOR AGGRO: <br />
-50% Beats (20 cards) <br />
You must have constant threats and attacks to keep your opponent dying and being slammed ino the ground. Also, the fatser they are, the better, and thigns like boot ands wasperines help alot with this. Cretures are usually the best startegy for this, but cald can hold its own for an aggro deck without playing many cretures, but it is best suited for control. Some examples of cards for this slot are Wasperine, Vellup, Warrior&#39;s Boots, Aerial Flist, and trust me, the list goes on. <br />
-25% Discard (10 cards) <br />
You gotta be able to stop Speags SOMEHOW. Shockwave, Tital Wave, Undertow, and several other things give this slot a fair chance. Also needed are relic bashers and mabye even weenie knockers liek Beam of Light and Relic Stalkers. The discard is best used for a final punch to the gut before a wave of attacks slams into the defender. Not as many options here, but still enough to give you some choice to fit into your deck, depending on your energy curve (the cost of your cards) <br />
-25% Utility (10 cards) <br />
Well, every plan has a weakness. THis one could, say, A kybar&#39;s teeth Jasker&#39;s mask deck that lays out its giant hand every turn. You only cna play your pathetic men in response and run into a wall of stone. Best used for this spot are board cleaers, burn, and drawing. So many options aviable here, like tradewinds, T-quake, Ormie, Burshfire, Vortex of Knowledge, the list simply goes on. <br />
<br />
Magis: <br />
Generall, starting cards tend to be important in aggro. And themes are okay too. For example, in aderial aggro, Delia is best complemented by a team of vellups and giant vellups to deliever early, quick, insane beats. The second magi should be someone who gains quick energy advantage and can play some utility and discard to bring back advantage quickly. You might put a little control in here to gain back advantage for sure. The last should be a finisher that piles through whatever is left quickly, at the use of all it&#39;s resources nessecary. Plenty of examples for each regions, I can&#39;t go over them all, but a general idea for Aderial, perhaps, Might be: <br />
Delia, Sorreah, Elios. <br />
<br />
CONTROL: Short for, well. Okay. It&#39;s just control. You choose if your opponent plays things, keeps cretures in play, and basically makes sure the opponent doesnt get the upper hand while you build up cards and energy for any sort of random finishing blow. This blow should also have some sort of running theme that goes along with your deck. <br />
<br />
RECIPE FOR CONTROL: <br />
40% Permission (16 cards) <br />
Basically deciding what your opponent does, and when. Some examples would be Phrup, Wellisk, Will of Orothe, and entangle. You must have skill in order to decide when to use these and also have skill to decide how to use these. Control needs a serious player to pilot and is not always fun to play with or against, but it does kind of work ruthlessly effectively. <br />
25% Draw (10 cards) <br />
To control properly you must have three kinds of advantage: Card advantages (more cards in play and in hand), Tempo advantage (play things before your opponent) and Energy Advantage (uh.. have more energy than your opponent?). Cheap drawing spells/relics are best, but other things can be used or splashed. Tradewinds is a long time victim of splashing, or instance, but trust me, there is plenty of in-region draw, try to stick to that.<br />
25% Disruption (10 cards)<br />
You also must be able to gain tempo and energy advantage, even if you need to ‘cheat’ a little. That does not mean energizing for three extra, it means playing shockwave on their 19e Furok. Many things fit here, like discard (shockwave, beam of light), sweepers (Cataclysm, T-quake, Ormie), and hand  (gasp! a bad word! anyway, stuff like vulbor). It is okay to be unfair.<br />
10% Win! (4 cards)<br />
Using perhaps a highly protected Cawh, Dark Cragnoc, or Colossus wins games, if backed up by the necessaries. Many ways to win. Some more original than others. Try and stay original, it adds a hint of fun to control.<br />
<br />
Magis:<br />
Try using things that manipulate things conditionally, as you likely be able to set up that condition somehow. Vorga, Agram, and Qwade are good examples for control magi. Sometimes, a good drawer with low energize is placed first. Basically, and two control magi with a drawer or staller in the front works.<br />
For example, in Core control, a popular, choice, a lineup could be Warrada (stall and her wonderful drawing ring), Then Morag and Qwade.<br />
<br />
COMBO: Yay! more abbreviations! Short for combination, this deck sets up some sort of insanely cool or weird win condition after spending an insane amount of time drawing, preparing, and stalling. Combo is limited, in MN:D, though, as there are not many ways to manipulate the game as there are not many resources, just cards and energy, so energy is usually how the combo is broken.  Combos usually involve certain cards, and therefore, must draw them.<br />
<br />
RECIPE FOR COMBO:<br />
40% Pieces (16 cards)<br />
In a non-broken combo deck, usually about  this many cards are included to abuse the combo that is gained from these cards. Some examples would be Scroll of Fire and lots of mass damagers for cheap, Jasker’s mask with energize abuse and expensive goodies, and few others. As I noted before, combo is rather limited in MN:D.<br />
0-20% Stall (0-8 cards)<br />
Stuff like (I sound like a broken record with all this shockwave business, but yes,) shockwave is good for this slot, along with Vim and Vigor, Speag, Ormie, and Cataslysm, although the former isn’t always combo-friendly (multi region stuff.) This is included in some decks and left  out in others, depending on the solidnes of the card draw, magis, and combo in questions.<br />
40-60% Draw (16-24 cards)<br />
You need to get your combo, and make it work! The first two magis are usually completely devoted to this slot, or the setup of the last slot, so they can draw anyways, so you’ve got a bit of time to fill, and you might as well draw your combos. Some examples would, be, of course, Frusk, Tradewinds, Vortex of Knowledge, Sea Barl, Deep Barl, Agovo, Book Of Ages, Drowl, Warrada’s ring, Secrets of the book, and so much more. The Possibilites are endless.<br />
<br />
Magis:<br />
This completely depends on the combo, but, as usual, the first two magis are staller drawers that sit and draw like work horses until the last one comes around. An example for a Jasker deck could be:<br />
Tiller, Ahdar, and finally any KT magi with a biggo energize. <br />
<br />
So there you go, basically, when your building a deck, tyr to focus it on one of these strategies.<br />
<br />
I gotta jet, lots of science homework to do!! (unless someone can D-mail me tonight everything about Aristotle!)<br />
<br />
-Matt<br />
<br />
Nest week: Combining the archtypes!<br />
Aggro-control, control-combo, and Aggro-combo (does it even exist?)<br />
